  <section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00001">
  <title>Learning Objectives</title>
  <para id="para-00001"><emphasis effect="bold">After completing this section, you should be able to:</emphasis></para>
  <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00001">
  <item>Evaluate the basics of car purchasing.</item>
  <item>Compute purchase payments and identify the related interest cost.</item>
  <item>Compare purchase payments for new and used cars.</item>
  <item>Identify and contrast the pros and cons of purchasing versus leasing a car.</item>
  <item>Investigate the types of car insurance.</item>
  <item>Solve application problems involving owning and maintaining a car.</item>
  </list>
  </section>
  <para id="para-00002">To buy, or to lease—that is the question. Whether having a new car every 3 years or buying a car for the long term is the primary issue in this decision. considering expiring warranties and repair costs are some of the items we will look at in this section. There are advantages and disadvantages to both paths, such as where you live, whether you have a garage, and the cost of credit are some of the things to consider. Before you make your decision, study this module to make sure it is the right decision for you.</para>
  <section id="sect-00002">
  <title>Purchasing a Car</title>
  <para id="para-00003">The first thing you should do is decide what car is right for you, what options are necessary, and your general driving habits, like how many miles per year you drive. Researching new cars in a tech-savvy world makes the process fairly straightforward. Most car dealerships have websites as well, where you can find explanations of the various options offered on a vehicle, and most car manufactures offer packages, which contain groups of options.</para>
  <para id="para-00004">You can research the pros and cons of any model on the internet, search reviews, and read car magazine articles. You do not have to have a vast knowledge of car mechanics to take advantage of car magazine articles, even though the auto industry has its own lingo and reading a car magazine may seem like reading a foreign language. However, if you can dedicate enough time, eventually you will have learned enough to differentiate between models.</para>
  <para id="para-00005">Once you have chosen your vehicle, get preapproved for a loan. Figure out how much you can afford to put down, and how much you can pay per month. They say that a car depreciates by 20% the minute you drive it off the lot. Therefore, making a minimum down payment of 20% makes a lot of sense. And remember that a good credit score may help you negotiate a better interest rate. You can then shop around for the best deal. Often, the financing opportunity offered by the dealership will be the best. There are several loan calculators available online—for example, <link url="https://openstax.org/r/car_loan_calculator">NerdWallet offers a calculator</link> for loans on the purchase of a car—or you can use a formula to figure out your monthly payment. You always have a choice as to whether you want to finance a car through the dealership or by getting a loan from a bank.</para>
  <note class="formula" id="note-00002">
  <para id="para-00006">The formula to calculate a monthly car payment is</para>
  <equation id="eq-00001"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>P</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>[</mo> <mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></mrow> <mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></equation>
  <para id="para-00013" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">where <emphasis effect="italic">PMT</emphasis> = payment, <emphasis effect="italic">P</emphasis> = principal, <emphasis effect="italic">r</emphasis> = interest rate, <emphasis effect="italic">n</emphasis> = number of payments per year, and <emphasis effect="italic">t</emphasis> = time in years.</para>
  </note>
  <example id="exam-00001">
  <title>Calculating Your Car Payment</title>
  <exercise id="exer-00001">
  <problem id="prob-00001">
  <para id="para-00007">Suppose you decide to borrow $25,000 to purchase a new car. The interest rate is 7% and the length of the loan is 5 years. What will your car payment be?</para>
  </problem>
  <solution id="sol-00001">
  <para id="para-00008">Using the formula:</para>
  <equation id="eq-00002"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>25</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>000</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.07</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>[</mo> <mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.07</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>12</mn><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>5</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></msup></mrow> <mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>145.83</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>.29459</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>495.03</mn></mrow></math></equation>
  <para id="para-00009" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">Your monthly car payment will be $495.03.</para>
  </solution>
  </exercise>
  </example>
